{"questionId":"19195","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Points in the plane are subjected to a transformation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> in which the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is transformed to the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;where</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>x</mi><mo>'</mo></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>y</mi><mo>'</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>x</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>y</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>C</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>D</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> form a square.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>the four sides are equal in length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>5</mn></mfenced></math><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Grad&nbsp;AB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>Grad&nbsp;BC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so product of gradients&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>,&nbsp;therefore <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AB</mtext></math> is perpendicular&nbsp;to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BC</mtext></math><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>therefore <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math> is a square<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19195","referenceCode":"20N.1.AHL.TZ0.F_7b.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Show that the points A(1, 4), B(4, 8), C(8, 5), D(5, 1) form a square.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Matrix transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}